questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice migrated to Java 21 Virtual Threads experiences severe performance degradation and latency spikes under load. Thread dumps reveal that many virtual threads are pinned to their carrier threads. The following snippet is from the payment processing service:

java
@Component
public class PaymentRegistry {
    private final Map<String, PaymentStatus> cache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public synchronized PaymentStatus getOrFetchStatus(String paymentId, PaymentClient client) {
        return cache.computeIfAbsent(paymentId, id -> {
            // Blocking HTTP call via external client
            return client.fetchFromRemote(id);
        });
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue in a Spring Boot application where database updates performed inside a `CompletableFuture` chain are occasionally not committed, or they are committed even when a runtime exception occurs. The code looks like this:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired private OrderRepository repository;

    @Transactional
    public CompletableFuture<Void> processOrderAsync(Order order) {
        return CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            order.setStatus(Status.PROCESSING);
            repository.save(order);
            if (order.getAmount() > 1000) {
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Limit exceeded");
            }
        });
    }
}

You are debugging a production latency issue where a service processes incoming requests using a dedicated, bounded ThreadPoolExecutor named `customExecutor`. The pipeline is constructed as follows:

java
CompletableFuture<String> stage1 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUserData(userId), customExecutor);
CompletableFuture<Void> stage2 = stage1.thenApply(this::enrichData)
                                        .thenAccept(this::saveToDatabase);

During peak traffic, profiling shows that `enrichData` and `saveToDatabase` are frequently executed by the `ForkJoinPool.commonPool` or even the main request-handling threads, rather than the `customExecutor`, leading to CPU starvation on unrelated tasks.
